[Comedy Bang Bang](http://www.earwolf.com/show/comedy-bang-bang/) is an alt-comedy improv podcast published at least weekly since 2009. Each episode features one or more guests, who may be playing themselves or an improvised character. Since its inception, there have been 556 episodes with 432 unique guests.

At the end of the year, listeners vote on the best episodes of the year (Thanksgiving-to-Thanksgiving), which are compiled in year-end Best Of episodes that are published over the Christmas-New Year break. Paul F. Tompkins, the most frequent CBB guest, typically cohosts these shows with the show's host, Scott Aukerman.

This year, there was a lot of Scott-and-Paul talk in the Best Ofs about the frequency in which Paul appears in Best Of'd episodes, I decided to test whether this was because Paul makes episodes good, or it he's just in a lot of episodes. To do this, I used the statistical computing package [R](https://www.r-project.org/), alongside the [tidyverse](https://www.tidyverse.org/) and [rvest](https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/rvest/rvest.pdf) packages.

I scraped the data directly from the Earwolf website using [this script](https://pastebin.com/an7XdqJy), and then performed the data treatment using [this other script](https://pastebin.com/XfY6BLzn).

[Here is a plot](https://i.imgur.com/3iR3yyl.png) which shows every episode of Comedy Bang Bang, highlighting the Best Of'd episodes, and color-coding the top 9 most frequent guests. You'll notice that the red PFT dot is very frequently highlighted. This is especially true in 2017.

Then, for shits and giggles, I constructed a very simple linear model, where I tried to predict whether an episode was Best Of'd based on which guests (of the guests with a dozen appearances or more) were in the episode. I want to emphasize, **these stats are bad stats and not rigorous.** Don't read too much into them, they're just for fun. 

